lignedmetricprovidesahighlyreliable,human-alignedstandard\nnecessary for advancing AV-Gen assessment.\n4.5 Reward Model of Test-Time Best-of-N Scaling for AV-Gen\nWe deploy our metric\nTable3:Cross-metricgeneralizationinBoNscaling.Rows:\nReward Signal; Cols: Evaluation Metric. Diagonal (gray)\nas an active reward\nexcluded. Our metric yields the highest off-diagonal per-\nfor test-time Best-of-N\nformance. Best valid results bolded.\n(BoN) scaling. Using\nBoNRewardAV-AlignJavisScoreDeSync RALI OurMetric\nLTX-2, we generate\ncandidates for each Random 0.0698 0.0714 1.0824 0.3744 0.8820\nvisual anchor and com- +AV-Align 0.2116 0.0710 1.0570 0.3694 3.2385\npare against existing +JavisScore 0.0725 0.1633 1.0280 0.3901 1.7417\nevaluators (AV-Align, +DeSync 0.0536 0.0756 0.1630 0.3756 0.4403\nJavisScore, DeSync, +RALI 0.0726 0.0845 1.0880 0.4596 1.7561\nRALI). +Ours 0.1439 0.0934 1.0336 0.3959 5.0589\nTo prevent reward hacking, we strictly analyze cross-metric generalization, ex-\ncludingdiagonalcaseswheretherewardandevaluationmetricsmatch.Asshown\nin Table 3, traditional metrics yield poor cross-generalization, often underper-\nforming random selection. Conversely, our metric (+ Ours) achieves the highest\noff-diagonal scores across three of four independent metrics. This confirms our\n\n=== PAGE 13 ===\nAdapting Omni-LLM as a Reference-Free AV Sync Evaluator 13\nmetric captures universal causal-semantic synchronization, proving effective for\nAV-Gen supervision.\n4.6 Ablation Studies\nHow should an Omni-LLM parameterize rating scores for continuous evalua-\ntion? Wevalidateourcontinuousscoringdesignbyablatingalternativeformula-\ntions.WecompareScalar Ranking against:1)Scalar Regression,regressing\nranksviaMSE;2)ScoreasText-CE,autoregressivelygeneratingscorestrings;\nand 3) Score as Text-KL, minimizing KL divergence over digit probabilities.\nAs Table 4 shows, Table 4: Ablation on score representation strategies.\nmapping contextual Score-RepresentationNDCGKendallPair-ACCTop-1ACC\njudgments into rigid ScalarRegression 0.8843 0.1628 58.84 19.41\nbounds or discrete tokens ScoreasText-CE 0.8817 0.1141 56.19 27.03\nScoreasText-KL 0.8787 0.1324 56.94 22.44\ninduces severe drop.\nScalarRanking 0.9353 0.4515 71.07 55.80\nText-based decoding and scalar regression yield poor correlation (Kendall ≤\n0.1628) and discrimination (Top-1 Acc < 28%). Conversely, Scalar Ranking\npreserves relative topological order, boosting Pairwise Accuracy to 71.07% and\nTop-1 Accuracy to 55.80%. This confirms continuous rank optimization avoids\nthe quantization and framing biases of discrete vocabularies.\nHow does each component contribute? To\nTable5:Ablationstudyonthecore\ncomponents of our proposed frame-\nevaluate the individual impact of our core\nwork.\nmethodological components, we incremen-\ntallyablatetheuseoftheSynthSyncdataset SynthSyncPFTRLNDCG PairACC(%)\ntraining, Preference Alignment Fine-Tuning × × × 0.8531 51.02\n(PFT), and Reinforcement Learning (RL). ✓ ✓ ✓ × × × 0 0 . . 9 9 3 2 5 2 3 4 ( (+ + 8 9 . . 1 6 % %) ) 7 6 1 6 . . 1 6 6 0 ( ( + + 3 3 0 9 . . 5 5 % % ) )\nThe results in Table 5 demonstrate the ef- ✓ ✓ ✓ 0.9435(+10.6%)72.38(+41.9%)\nfectiveness of each component.\nHow do different reward Table 6: Ablation study of different reward functions\nusedintheR-GRPOframework,comparingpairwise,list-\nformulations impact the\nwise, and dual reward strategies.\nRL post-training? We\ninvestigate the impact of Reward NDCG MRR Kendall PairACC(%)\ndifferent reward formula- PFT-baseline 0.9353 0.7316 0.4515 71.16\ntions during R-GRPO post- PairReward 0.9396 (+0.5%) 0.7584 (+3.7%) 0.4700 (+4.1%) 71.70 (+0.8%)\ntraining by comparing ListReward 0.9339 (-0.2%) 0.7371 (+0.8%) 0.4267 (-5.5%) 70.34 (-1.2%)\npairwise, listwise, and\nDualRewards0.9435(+0.9%)0.7674(+4.9%)0.4899(+8.5%)72.38(+1.7%)\ncomposite dual-reward\nstrategies against the PFT baseline. As shown in Table 6, optimizing solely\nwithaPairRewardyieldsconsistentbutmarginalimprovementsacrossallmet-\nrics. Conversely, relying exclusively on a List Reward degrades rank correla-\ntion (Kendall’s τ drops by 5.5%) and pairwise accuracy, indicating that macro-\nscopic distributional optimization alone can destabilize fine-grained local order-\ning.However,integratingbothconstraintsintoaDualRewardstrategyachieves\nthe optimal balance. This composite approach establis\n\n=== PAGE 14 ===\n14 Y. Qian et al.\nperformance, yielding a 4.9% relative improvement in MRR and an 8.5% im-\nprovement in Kendall’s τ over the baseline. This confirms that global structural\nconsistency and local comparative accuracy are mutually reinforcing objectives\nduring latent continuous policy optimization.\nHow does the exploration variance of Gaussian policy impact RL-post training?\nIn our R-GRPO framework, the deterministic Table 7: Ablation on the ex-\nploration standard deviation (σ)\nscalar output is reparameterized as the cen-\nused in the Gaussian policy dur-\ntral manifold of an unconstrained exploratory\ning R-GRPO. An intermediate vari-\nGaussian policy. Table 7 illustrates the sen-\nanceyieldstheoptimalbalancebe-\nsitivity of our framework to the chosen stan- tweenlistwiseexplorationandpol-\ndard deviation (σ) governing this exploration icy stability, achieving peak align-\nspace. When the variance is too constrained ment across all metrics.\n(σ = 2.0), the model lacks the necessary ex-\nσ NDCG KendallPair ACC\nploratory range to discover optimal listwise\ntrajectories,yieldingsub-optimalrankcorrela- 2.0 0.9366 0.4625 71.56\ntion(Kendall’sτ of0.4625)andpairwiseaccu- 2.5 0.9435 0.4899 72.38\nracy(71.56%).Conversely,anexcessivelylarge 10.0 0.9405 0.4768 71.70\nvariance (σ =10.0) introduces severe noise\ninto the rollout sampling, which destabilizes the proximal trust region and de-\ngrades the optimization gradient. We find that an intermediate variance of\nσ = 2.5 provides the optimal equilibrium—affording the policy enough flexi-\nbility to explore complex global topologies while remaining stable enough to\naccurately exploit learned comparative margins. This configuration achieves the\npeak Pairwise Accuracy of 72.38% and an NDCG of 0.9435.\n4.7 Qualitative Visualization\nTo complement the quantitative leaderboard, Fig. 6 shows four SyncBench ex-\namples comparing generated audio against the ground-truth pattern with the\ncorrespondingevaluatorscores.Ourmetricconsistentlypenalizesmissingacous-\ntic events, premature or delayed responses, timbre mismatch, and event-count\ninconsistency, more faithfully reflecting whether the audio preserves the causal-\nsemanticstructureimpliedbythevisualcontentthanlow-levelsignalmatching.\n5 Conclusion\nWe identified a critical bottleneck in audio-visual generation: the lack of met-\nrics capable of understanding intricate physical interactions between sight and\nsound,astraditionalmetricsfailonmodernartifactsbyassumingstructuralcor-\nrectness and relying on simple temporal offsets. To overcome this, we present a\ncontinuous, reference-free framework for causal-semantic synchronization, built\nonSynthSync,adatasetofauthenticgenerativefailuresrankedviahumanprefer-\nence.ByreplacingthediscretelanguageheadofanOmni-LLMwithacontinuous\nlatent projection and optimizing the listwise score distribution via Real-Valued\n\n=== PAGE 15 ===\nAdapting Omni-LLM as a Reference-Free AV Sync Evaluator 15\nFig.6:QualitativevisualizationexamplesfromSyncBench.Upperleft(Motorcycle\nEngine):thegroundtruthshowsclearengine-reveventsalignedwiththevisualmotion\nandscoreshighest;FoleyCrafterisdelayed,whileLOVAmissestheacousticsignature.\nUpper right (Wood Chop): the ground truth preserves sharp, periodic chopping\ntransients; CAFA keeps approximate timing but mismatches timbre, while LOVA is\nlargely irrelevant. Lower left (Soft Placement): the ground truth contains subtle\nyet well-aligned contact sounds; MelQCD misses events and responds prematurely,\nwhile FoleyControl shows severe timbre distortion and event-count mismatch. Lower\nright (Chimes):thegroundtruthreflectssynchronizedchimeactivations;MMAudio\nrespondsprematurely,whileFoleyControlisdominatedbynoisewithincorrecttimbre.\nAcross all cases, our metric better matches causal-semantic synchronization quality\nthan superficial signal similarity.\nGroup Relative Policy Optimization (R-GRPO ), we bridge the gap between rel-\native human perception and the need for an absolute, deployable metric. Our\nestimator achieves state-of-the-art human preference alignment and also gen-\neralizes robustly across metrics when deployed as a test-time Best-of-N reward\nmodel.Thisdualrole—asbothareliableevaluatorandanactionablerewardsig-\nnal—advancesaudio-visualassessmentfromlow-levelsignalcorrelationtophys-\nically grounded causality.\nAcknowledgements\nThis work was supported by the Zhejiang Key Laboratory of Advanced Intelli-\ngent Warehousing and Logistics Equipment under Grant No. 2024E10007. This\nworkwaspartiallysupportedbyRGCCollaborativeResearchFund(No.C5055-\n24G),theStart-upFundofTheHongKongPolytechnicUniversity(No.P0045999),\nthe Seed Fund of the Research Institute for Smart Ageing (No. P0050946), and\nTsinghua-PolyUJointResearchInitiativeFund(No.P0056509),andPolyUUGC\nfunding (No. P0053716).\n\n=== PAGE 16 ===\n16 Y. Qian et al.\nReferences\n1. Benita, R., Finkelson, M., Halperin, T., Sterkin, G., Adi, Y.: Cafa: a controllable\nautomaticfoleyartist.In:ProceedingsoftheIEEE/CVFInternationalConference\non Computer Vision. pp. 15917–15926 (2025)\n2. Brokman, J., Rachmil, O., Hofman, O., Betser, R., Giloni, A., Vainshtein, R.,\nKojima,H.:Training-freedetectionoftext-to-videogenerationsviaover-coherence.\nIn:ProceedingsoftheIEEE/CVFWinterConferenceonApplicationsofComputer\nVision. pp. 3993–4003 (2026)\n3. Brooks, T., Peebles, B., Holmes, C., DePue, W., Guo, Y., Jing, L., Schnurr, D.,\nTaylor,J.,Luhman,T.,Luhman,E.,Ng,C.,Wang,R.,Ramesh,A.:Videogenera-\ntionmodelsasworldsimulators.https://openai.com/index/video-generation-\nmodels-as-world-simu